<keyLead pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,159,798,819]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">-</emphasis>
Antennomere 4 with tomentose pubescence (Figs. 10, 26, 33, 43, 50); mandibles curved from apical half (
<figureCitation box="[1237,1329,798,820]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1474,1498]" captionTargetBox="[158,1430,525,1451]" captionTargetId="figure-165@3.[158,1430,525,1451]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Xanthopygus xanthopygus (Nordmann). 1. Dorsal view of left mandible, scale bar = 2.1 mm. 2. Dorsal view of the right mandible, scale bar = 2.1 mm. 3. Maxilla, scale bar = 1.0 mm. 4. Hypopharynx and labial palps, scale bar = 0.8 mm. 5. Prosternum, scale bar = 1.8 mm. 6. Meso- and metaventrite, scale bar = 2.6 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048485" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048485/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
Figs. 1 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1303,1315,798,819]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">–</emphasis>
2
</figureCitation>
, 7, 40, 47); eyes as long as 1/3-2/5 length of head (Figs. 7, 23, 30, 40, 47); head appearing convex (Figs. 7, 23, 30, 40, 47); sternite 6 with single anterior transverse line (Fig. 9)..................................................................... 3
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,710,1495]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<keyLead pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
2. Antennomere 3 clearly longer than 2 (
<figureCitation box="[601,674,886,908]" captionStart="FIGURES 15–18" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1510,1534]" captionTargetBox="[169,1311,186,1480]" captionTargetId="figure-23@10.[156,1432,181,1486]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 15–18. Xanthopygus luctuosus (Blanchard). 15. Habitus photograph. 16. Pronotum. 17. Sternites 6–8. 18. Antenna. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048493" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048493/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
); pronotum microsculpture polygon shaped; tergite 6 sparsely punctate; tip of paramere emarginate (
<figureCitation box="[440,556,916,938]" captionStart="FIGURES 19–21" captionStartId="11.[151,264,782,806]" captionTargetBox="[197,1385,181,753]" captionTargetId="figure-16@11.[197,1390,181,758]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 19–21. Aedeagus of X. luctuosus (Blanchard). 19. Dorsal view. 20. Lateral view. 21. Detail of paramere, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048495" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048495/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Figs. 19, 21</figureCitation>
).............................................................. 
