<figureCitation box="[565,633,1003,1026]" captionStart="FIGURES 47–50" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1921,1945]" captionTargetBox="[151,1430,601,1891]" captionTargetId="figure-211@22.[149,1437,597,1897]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 47–50. Xanthopygus xanthopygus (Nordmann). 47. Habitus photograph. 48. Pronotum. 49. Sternites 6–8. 50. Antenna. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048518" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048518/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Fig 50</figureCitation>
); pronotum densely punctate, typically with three rows of punctures on each half beside median line (
<figureCitation box="[419,491,1033,1055]" captionStart="FIGURES 47–50" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1921,1945]" captionTargetBox="[151,1430,601,1891]" captionTargetId="figure-211@22.[149,1437,597,1897]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 47–50. Xanthopygus xanthopygus (Nordmann). 47. Habitus photograph. 48. Pronotum. 49. Sternites 6–8. 50. Antenna. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048518" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048518/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Fig. 48</figureCitation>
); sternite 
<quantity box="[585,622,1033,1055]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.778" pageId="25" pageNumber="176" unit="in" value="7.0">7 in</quantity>
males with porose structure (
<figureCitation box="[906,975,1033,1055]" captionStart="FIGURES 47–50" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1921,1945]" captionTargetBox="[151,1430,601,1891]" captionTargetId="figure-211@22.[149,1437,597,1897]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 47–50. Xanthopygus xanthopygus (Nordmann). 47. Habitus photograph. 48. Pronotum. 49. Sternites 6–8. 50. Antenna. Not to scale." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6048518" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6048518/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">Fig. 49</figureCitation>
)........................ 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Nordmann" baseAuthorityYear="1837" box="[1288,1436,1033,1055]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Xanthopygus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="176" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="xanthopygus">
<emphasis box="[1288,1436,1033,1055]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">X. xanthopygus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,710,1495]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<keyLead pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
- Antennomere 4 subquadrate (Figs. 10, 26, 33, 43); pronotum not densely punctate, typically with two or less rows of punctures on each half beside median line (Figs. 8, 24, 31, 41); sternite 
<quantity box="[814,851,1092,1114]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.778" pageId="25" pageNumber="176" unit="in" value="7.0">7 in</quantity>
males without porose structure (Figs. 9, 25, 32, 42)..... 4
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,710,1495]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<keyLead pageId="25" pageNumber="176">4. Head and pronotum with medium to large size punctures (Figs. 7–8, 40–41); pronotum with 1–2 dense rows of punctures on each half beside median line (Figs. 8, 41); abdominal segments 4–6 with iridescent overtones under strong light (Figs. 7, 40). ................................................................................................... 5</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,710,1495]" pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
<keyLead pageId="25" pageNumber="176">
